[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The proposed introduction of a residence test for civil [bold]Legal Aid[bold] claimants, so as to limit [bold]Legal Aid[bold] to those with a “strong connection” with the UK[bold]Asylum Aid is very concerned that the proposed ‘residence test’ 
[normal]– generally understood as one year’s legal residence in the UK – 
[normal]is 
[normal]incompatible with human rights.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It will directly affect our clients whose applications for asylum have been refused, but who rely on 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] to bring new information about their situati
[normal]on (or ‘fresh claims’) before the Home Office. This right is essential, given that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1. Fre[bold]sh asylum c[bold]laims[bold] and destitute asylum seekers[bold] [bold]It is unclear from the consultation document whether the Ministry of Justice proposes to grant access to 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] as soon as a fresh claim for asylum has been submitted or, as it appears from the consultation
[normal] proposals, whether 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] will only be granted once an application has been accepted by the Government as amounting to a fresh claim. This needs to be clarified as a matter of urgency. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If it is the latter, then in a situation where a person submits a
[normal] fresh claim but the government refuses to treat it as such, the applicant would not have a 
[normal]right of appeal. Under the present system the only legal remedy open to a person in t
[normal]his situation would be to seek J
[normal]udicial 
[normal]R
[normal]eview – but under these proposals, whe
[normal]re a person has no right to reside, access to 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] for 
[normal]J
[normal]udicial 
[normal]R
[normal]eview would also be curtailed. This has the potential to deny access to justice for vulnerable asylum seekers and is therefore incompatible with human rights legislation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Asylum Aid’s work advising destitute asylum seekers consistently finds that at least 50% of the clients advised have legitimate merits for accessing 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] to reopen their cases. This could be to undertake fresh asylum claims or to commence judicial rev
[normal]iew proceedings as a result of the Home Office not following their own established policies and procedures.
[normal] This vulnerable client group already faces extreme barriers accessing 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] for further advice on 
[normal]their cases. This is why Asylum Aid has devel
[normal]oped outreach advice surgeries to undertake this work, outside the scope of 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal]. Once we have established the merits of the case, we use this as evidence to persuade legal providers to take these people on because – despite the barriers they have fac
[normal]ed – they should be entitled to access 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal]. This can then also assist to resolve destitution problems. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]Ministry of Justice 
[normal]proposals 
[normal]would
[normal] establish further barriers for this vulnerable client group, making it more difficult for them to access 
[normal]justice and exacerbating their destitution. Moreover, preventing access to justice for people with legitimate human rights claims in this way may well be incompatible with human rights legislation to which the government has signed up. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2. Fresh [bold]asylum[bold] claims and w[bold]omen [bold]Making it harder to get 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] for fresh claims has a disproportionate impact on women asylum seekers. This is because there are a range of factors that can make it harder for women to disclose their experiences at the time of their a
[normal]sylum claim and appeal. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These factors include: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I would also d
[normal]raw your attention to the situation described by the campaign group Save Justice, whose client was recognised as a refugee and was able to access 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] to apply for a non-molestation order against her violent and dangerous ex-husband.
[normal] This potentially
[normal] life-saving provision would be lost under these proposals.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. Separated Asylum-Seeking Children [bold]Asylum Aid works to ensure separated asylum seeking children are kept safe from harm.
[normal] We are therefore deeply concerned about the potential impact that the
[normal] residence test could have on t
[normal]his extremely vulnerable 
[normal]group
[normal] of young people, and about the potential breaches of the 
[normal]Convention on the Rights of 
[normal]the Child, 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]legally binding international agreement w
[normal]hich the UK has ratified and 
[normal]which is applicable to all
[normal] children present in the United Kingdom.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Asylum Aid is particularly concerned 
[normal]that the introduction of a residence test would breach
[normal] Articles 
[normal]of the Convention, including:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. Assessing the Residence Test [bold]Asylum Aid believes that the ability to assess a client under the proposed residence test will be an extremely complicated process and that, as such, only specialist immigration lawyers would be competent to undertake this work. If this reform is implement
[normal]ed, it would be necessary to grant 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] to advise on this process. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Notwithstanding this concern, this is a complex area of law with significant scope for wrongful interpretation, particularly in the absence of concrete evidence to prove or dis
[normal]prove 
[normal]the right to reside. I
[normal]t is highly likely that people will be denied access to justice due to a misunderstanding of their eligibility.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The proposal that providers of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies [bold]should only be paid for work done on the case if the Court grants permission for the application to proceed[bold]The proposed changes to access to Judicial Review (JR) are likely to impact asylum seekers and refugees, as well as the charities who work with the
[normal]m, far beyond that anticipated in the consultation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Work to research, prepare and present a JR is often substantial, especially to address concerns in the handling of the most complex asylum claims. If implemented, this proposal would act as a 
[normal]disincentive for providers to undertake JR work even where merits are established, as any work prior to permission being granted by the court would have to be undertaken pro bono. This will make it very difficult for people facing destitution to access JR,
[normal] particularly to apply for urgent injunctions. It will also make it far more difficult to undertake strategic litigation work to test and develop the law, which by definition is work carried out at risk, with border line potential for success.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The govern
[normal]ment has emphasised that funding will remain in place for meritorious JRs, to be paid after the decision on merits; but few organisations will have the cash-flow resources to prepare a JR appropriately knowing that this work will not be recompensed for man
[normal]y months. As 
[normal]the 
[normal]I
[normal]mmigration 
[normal]L
[normal]aw 
[normal]P
[normal]ractitioners’ 
[normal]A
[normal]ssociation
[normal] 
[normal](ILPA) has argued recently
[normal], after a succession of cuts many 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] providers “cannot assume any more financial risk in their businesses”.
[normal] In practice, it will become a lasting challenge to fun
[normal]d upfront the work needed to file a JR, even where the merits of the case are immediately evident. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition
[normal], the underlying motive to sav
[normal]e public expenditure is 
[normal]questionable when one takes into account the fact that weak cases are already refused perm
[normal]ission to proceed. This mechanism is already in place to protect the public purse and strikes a fair balance. In urgent cases the merits of the case need to be kept under ongoing assessment, but the final decision on whether to grant 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] always rests
[normal] with the 
[normal]Legal Aid
[normal] Agency, not the provider. 
[normal]Restricting access to JRs would have the effect of limiting essential access to justice, even where there is an overwhelming need to correct an error in a previous decision. Some of the most vulnerable asylum 
[normal]seekers and refugees would be left without recourse to help to which they are entitled, including: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Asylum Aid is deeply concerned at this prospect. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Having borne witness over many years to the flaws and shortcomings in asylum decision-making, and the regularity with which the Home Office acts in breach of its own policies and procedures, the use of JR is paramount where there are legitimate concerns th
[normal]at the government has acted illegally or irrationally. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The government can maintain access to justice and more effectively save money by ensuring the Home Office takes a fair and competent approach to asylum claims earlier in the system. If the operation 
[normal]of the asylum system is aligned with the policies already in place, recourse to an expensive JR process will rightly become an exceptional occurrence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
